    <main>
      <article about="" typeof="schema:ScholarlyArticle">
        <h1 property="schema:name">Decentralised Linked Research Application</h1>

        <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
          <p>We observe that majority of the academic knowledge is presented as a package ie. binary file formats (like PDF, Word) merging structural, presentational, and behavioural layers, and often disconnected from other knowledge, due to policy, cost, or technical reasons. A side-effect is that, as research communication is still primarily driven by the constraints of the print medium, it makes it challenging for efficient machine-readable coordination on the Web. One open challenge here is the continuous advancement of creating, communicating, and consuming human and machine-accessible information suitable for the Web platform.</p>

          <p>In the earlier sections, we have discussed progress in research, standards, and practices towards different aspects of realising a decentralised information space. Each dataspace can be individually controlled with access controls for participating agents. Different applications can be implemented to operate on the same data, as well as send activities about the interactions about the data. In this section, we specifically discuss a set of requirements for the implementation of a clientside editor for decentralised article publishing, annotations and social interactions.</p>

          <p>By <q>Web publishing</q>, we include the notions of authoring and publishing any kind of unit of information for human and machine consumption, relating and linking to globally identifiable units of information, as well as their dissemination.</p>


          <p class="todo">Explain how dokieli is a <a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#socially-aware-read-write-linked-data">socially-aware read-write Linked Data</a> application.</p>

          <p>More specifically, we will address the following requirements for the research question on <span class="todo">X</span> in context of <a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#degree-of-control">degree of control</a> (as previously discussed in <cite>Decentralised Storage and Interoperable Applications</cite> section):</p>

           <ul>
            <li>Interoperable applications through Linked Data Notifications and Web Annotations.</li>
            <!-- <li>Creating human and machine-interpretable Web resources.</li> -->
            <li>Actors use their preferred WebID in clientside applications.</li>
            <li>Actors use their preferred clientside application to perform HTTP-based read-write operations on their where they have access to.</li>
            <li>Actors switch between applications without having to move or alter the schema of their data.</li>
            <li>Actors relocating data without having to change their preferred application.</li>
            <li>Querying and visualising statistical data from clientside applications.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>Finally, we will discuss the <a href="#dokieli-forces-functions">forces and functions in dokieli</a>.</p>

          <p>This section outlines key features and discusses design decisions made in dokieli as a domain-independent clientside application, and focuses its application in scholarly communication. I have original developed and am the maintainer of dokieli. I have served as an editor of W3C Note <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/annotation-html/" rel="cito:citesAsAuthority">Embedding Web Annotations in HTML</a></cite> as part of the W3C Web Annotation Working Group.</p>

          <section id="decentralised-linked-notifications-and-annotations" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#decentralised-linked-notifications-and-annotations">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Decentralised Linked Notifications and Annotations</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>The functional and non-functional requirements from the <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/ldp-ucr/">Linked Data Platform Use Cases and Requirements</a></cite> (<abbr title="Linked Data Platform Use Cases and Requirements">LDP-UCR</abbr>) are applicable for authoring, publishing, and sharing content. In order to represent different units of information in social and scholarly communication, Linked Data <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#vocabularies">vocabularies</a> can be used.</p>

              <p>By using different arrangements of LDN, WA, AP, LDP mechanisms and related vocabularies, scholarly and social activities can be systematically discovered for a variety of use cases. Decentralised notifications and annotations surrounding an article can be determined as follows:</p>

              <ul>
                <li id="subject-annotation-service">Resource asserts the location of a preferred service for maintaining annotations about the the subject resource (via <code>oa:annotationService</code>)</li>
                <li id="subject-inbox">Resource asserts the location of a service that receives and serves notifications about the subject resource (via <code>ldp:inbox</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-storage">An individual's profile asserting their preferred storage location (via <code>pim:storage</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-outbox">An individual's profile asserting the location of their activities (via <code>as:outbox</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-index">An individual's profile asserting their type index registrations (via <code>solid:publicTypeIndex</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-knows-profile-storage">Members of an individual's social graph (via eg. <code>foaf:knows</code>) asserting their preferred storage location</li>
                <li id="profile-knows-profile-outbox">Members of an individual's social graph asserting the location of their activities</li>
                <li id="profile-knowns-profile-index">Members of an individual's social graph sharing their type index registration (via <code>solid:publicTypeIndex</code>)</li>
                <li id="inbox-annotation-known">Inbox or annotation service locations are known prior to interaction eg. trusted or used by a community.</li>
                <li id="inbox-annotation-manual">Inbox or annotation service locations are manually input to the system eg. not publicised or private.</li>
              </ul>

              <p>Applications can incrementally implement a combination of these approaches to deliver and discover distributed activities on the Web. For example, the preferred locations for general data storage, annotations and notifications for resources can be discovered, and used as input to create new resources eg. assigning an inbox for an annotation where the inbox location is derived from a profile's preferred location for a class of information. Thereby a chain of operations can be orchestrated for decentralised units of information.</p>

              <p>Figure X depicts an interplay of decentralised personal profiles, notifications, and annotations.</p>

              <figure class="todo">
                <figcaption>Interplay of Personal Profiles, Notifications, and Annotations</figcaption>
              </figure>
            </div>
          </section>


          <section id="implementing-a-read-write-application" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#implementing-a-read-write-application">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Implementing a Read-Write Application</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>In this section we demonstrate how the various standards described can be pieced together into an application designed for researchers to participate in the scholarly communication ecosystem autonomously. We highlight some scholarly communication use cases with <cite><a href="https://dokie.li/">dokieli</a></cite>, a clientside editor for decentralised article publishing, annotations and social interactions.</p>

              <p>dokieli implements the use cases pertaining to <a href="#decentralised-linked-notifications-and-annotations">Decentralised Linked Notifications and Annotations</a> as outlined earlier, as well as those specific to <a href="linked-data-notifications#scholarly-communication-notification-use-cases">scholarly communication</a>.</p>

              <p>dokieli is inherently a general-purpose authoring, annotating, and notifying application. While it implements use cases specific to research or scholarly communication, it is not constrained to it. For instance, dokieli is capable of rendering the following use cases from the W3C <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/">RDFa Use Cases: Scenarios for Embedding RDF in HTML</a></cite>: <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-1">Basic Structured Blogging</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-2">Publishing an Event - Overriding Some of the Rendered Data</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-3">Content Management Metadata</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-5">Web Clipboard</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-7">Advanced Data Structures</q>, and <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-8">Augmented Browsing for Scientists</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-9">Publishing a RDF Vocabulary</q>.</p>

              <p>dokieli uses LDN to send and consume notifications: When a reader comments on a fragment of text in an article, the application discovers the article’s Inbox and sends a notification about the annotation. dokieli also consumes notifications from this Inbox to fetch and display the annotation as marginalia (<a href="#figure-dokieli-annotation">figure 2</a>). A reader can share a dokieli-enabled article with their contacts; dokieli discovers each contact’s Inbox and sends a notification there (<a href="#figure-dokieli-share">figure 3</a>). When editing an article, the author can add a citation. If an Inbox is discovered in the cited article, dokieli sends a notification there to indicate what part of the article was cited by whom and where. dokieli-enabled articles also consume citation notifications to display these metrics for the author and other readers (<a href="#figure-dokieli-citation">figure 4</a>).</p>


<!--
<pre>
*** memento, immutable.. internet archive features
</pre>
-->


              <p>In this section we describe dokieli's architecture along the following main areas:</p>

              <ul>
                <li>Actors can use their own WebIDs to identify themselves with, and have their profile information known to dokieli.</li>
                <li>Actors can publish and consume human and machine-readable (Linked Data), and decide where they are made available from and the conditions.</li>
                <li>Actors can use the notification system to announce and consume information, as well as to facilitate discovery and reuse.</li>
              </ul>

              <section id="deployment" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#deployment">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Deployment</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>dokieli employs two complementary deployment approaches: <em>single-page application</em> and <em>Web browser extension</em>.</p>

                  <p id="single-page-application">dokieli’s presentational and behavioural code layers can be included in Web pages in order to trigger them as active single-page applications. It is a smart client that allows different kinds of articles eg. academic, blog posts, news, to be authored and annotated from within Web browsers, without necessarily having them deployed from a server, ie. it can be used offline or on localhost. dokieli internally handles its content and structural and semantic representation based on user’s interactivity. Articles, profiles and their contact information, notifications, annotations with different motivations, for instance, can be read and written ubiquitously to any Web space with supporting HTTP methods and access control mechanisms.</p>

                  <p id="web-browser-extension">The Web browser extension is a thin wrapper around dokieli’s core code in order to embed itself in any HTML-based Web page on the Web. It inherits all of the features of a single-page application. While HTML based documents on the Web vary in their quality, dokieli’s write operations generate HTML+RDFa. One of the utilities for the extension is to have a consistent interface for annotating node or text selections on a Web page, building structured citations, creating derivations of Web resources as well as sharing parts of pages with ones contacts via notifications, without having a service dependency or being limited by the Web page’s UI.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="information-overview" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#information-overview">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Information Overview</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>Here we summarise the key protocols and data models that dokieli uses. Later, we will describe some key use cases in more detail.</p>

                  <p id="separation-of-concerns"><strong>Separation of Concerns</strong>: dokieli adopts <cite>progressive enhancement</cite> strategy for the structural, presentational, and behavioural layers to allow content and base functionality to be accessible through different media and devices. The content representation in HTML+RDFa that dokieli produces is accessible (readable by human and machine consumers) without requiring any CSS or JavaScript, ie. text-browser safe.</p>

                  <p id="human-machine-readable"><strong>Human and Machine-Readable</strong>: <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#why-rdfa">Why RDFa</a> explained having all human-visible content in HTML, and all structured statements be made in context of their content in RDFa, thereby a close association between structured data and visual locality. dokieli takes this approach when preparing documents, also to avoid any data duplication in the same document - adhering to the <abbr title="Don't Repeat Yourself">DRY</abbr> principle. The approach also helps to avoid the creation and usage of multiple data islands, ie. separately for humans and machines. Consequently, it has the advantage of not having any dependency on JavaScript in order to make the hidden machine-readable content be consumable from a human user interface. One exception to this rule is where dokieli allows authors to use embed Turtle, JSON-LD, or TriG data blocks in HTML typically for the purpose of non-prose information. We cannot know in advance what new kinds of information or data can be integrated into articles. So, dokieli sets no constraints on what information and how it can be be expressed in order to facilitate extensibility. Information can be expressed using different vocabularies, enabling reuse of existing data models and the addition of new semantic expressions.</p>

                  <p id="serialisations"><strong>Serialisations</strong>: dokieli can serialise articles, annotations, and notifications in HTML+RDFa, Turtle, and JSON-LD, depending on server content-negotiation. Articles are represented in HTML+RDFa so that information is usable by both humans and machine consumers while maintaining lowest requirements for publishing, eg. a single URL with full payload in HTML+RDFa can be accessible from any HTTP server. No additional requirements necessary from clients eg. JavaScript support and enabled, or servers eg. additional RDF based content-negotiation. For annotations and notifications, dokieli first meets interoperability requirements (for protocols and vocabularies), and remains flexible about the serialisation that servers prefer. Similarly for consuming content, it can work with any of the serialisations as mentioned.</p>

                  <p id="notification-inbox"><strong>Notification Inbox</strong>: An article or an arbitrary unit of information within may be associated with a notification inbox as per LDN's <code>ldp:inbox</code>. Articles containing the inbox relation is detected by dokieli, and used to send notifications about annotations that the user creates. While orthogonal, articles and inboxes can also preserve context in that a unique inbox can be associated with a unique version of an article, so that annotations will refer to the specific version of an article, as well as being specifically recalled through the unique inbox. dokieli also enables users to assign an inbox for the annotation that they are creating. This has the advantage that the annotation has its own inbox and it can be discovered by other means. This approach is supplemental to threaded annotations, ie. annotations on annotations, and can be used independently of the primary article. The assignment of the inbox comes from user's preferred location for an inbox for the purpose of announcements. It is based on Solid's Type Index Registration approach.</p>

                  <p id="annotation-service"><strong>Annotation Service</strong>: Articles can be associated with an annotation service located anywhere on the Web as per WA's <code>oa:annotationService</code>. Articles containing the annotation service relation is detected by dokieli, and offered as an optional location to send annotations to.</p>

                  <p id="license"><strong>License</strong>: Actors can assign any license and rights to their documents or any fragment within. All of the Creative Commons licenses are available from the dokieli UI for actors to use for articles and annotations. Notifications are licensed with CC0 1.0 Universal (public domain dedication).</p>

                  <p>dokieli applies the notion of articles, annotations, notifications, and profiles as described in <a href="structure-of-scholarly-informationunits-of-communication">Units of Communication</a>. Creating articles, annotations, and notifications in dokieli is intended to be done through its UI, and generates the required structured content.</p>

                  <p id="dokieli-articles"><strong>Articles</strong>: An article - in the most general sense of the term - may contain RDF classes like <code>schema:CreativeWork</code>, <code>sioc:Post</code>, <code>prov:Entity</code>, <code>schema:Article</code>, <code>as:Article</code>. While the body of annotations may also considered as articles in their own right, we reserve the usage of the term articles in particular to primary research documents typically containing structured prose. Actors can assign unique identifiers to any fragment of information.</p>

                  <p id="dokieli-annotations"><strong>Annotations</strong>: dokieli uses the Web Annotation <cite>Data Model</cite> and <cite>Vocabulary</cite> to express the annotations it creates, as well as implementing the Web Annotation <cite>Protocol</cite> in order to communicate with conforming annotation servers. dokieli initially prepares the annotation using the <cite>Embedding Web Annotations in HTML</cite> approach using RDFa, while subject to be re-serialised depending on content-negotiation. In fact, the examples in the W3C Note were derived from dokieli's application of the WA model and vocabulary for HTML+RDFa representations. An annotation has the <code>oa:Annotation</code> RDF class, contains a link to its body content and the target resource in which it is associated with. dokieli also uses the WA <cite>Selectors and States</cite> for selecting part of a resource and generating a dereferenceable HTTP URI. Annotations can be done at the document as well as sentence level.</p>

                  <p id="dokieli-notifications"><strong>Notifications</strong>: dokieli implements the LDN protocol to discover social and scholarly activities, such as annotations with different motivations, as well as sending contextual notifications to recipients (like documents or web-agents). A notification may have one of the following classes: <code>as:Announce</code>, <code>as:Like</code>, <code>as:Dislike</code>, <code>as:Relationship</code>.</p>

                  <p id="profiles"><strong>Profiles</strong>: Actors can use their personal WebIDs, and profile descriptions when interacting with the Web resources.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="http-operations" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#http-operations">
                <h3 property="schema:name">HTTP Operations</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>dokieli implements the <a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#crud-http">HTTP based CRUD operations</a> - create, update, and delete operations - and in particular, conforms to some of the clientside operations expected to communicate with LDP implementations.</p>

                  <p>Before dokieli makes a write request to a server, it triggers content-negotiation through <code>OPTIONS</code> and checks for <code>Allow</code> and <code>Accept-Post</code> headers in order to determine server's preferences. In the absence of successful negotiation, dokieli proceeds to make the request as per the required parameters of LDN, WAP, AP, and LDN. For example, <code>HTTP POST</code> with <code>application/ld+json</code> content type would be used for annotations and notifications, if a server's preference is not determined.</p>

                  <p>Articles typically use <code>text/html</code> with embedded RDFa. Where a server implements <code>GET</code> with <code>text/html</code>, and allows <code>PUT</code> for writing, the assumption is that it can allow payloads with <code>text/html</code> content type. HTML+RDFa is considered to be an important default for articles for being human and machine-readable. Hence, if a server is capable of handling HTML+RDFa, it will receive articles, annotations, and notifications in that form. Otherwise, dokieli will re-serialize the content into an alternative RDF syntax that the server prefers or capable of handling.</p>

                  <p><code>HTTP GET</code> is used to read resources. Article-level actions like <cite>New</cite>, <cite>Save</cite>, <cite>Save As</cite>, <cite>Reply</cite> use <code>HTTP PUT</code>. All annotation actions, notifications, as well as archiving functions use <code>HTTP POST</code> as per WAP, AP, and LDN.</p>

                  <aside id="http-patch">
                    <p>As of this writing, the reasons to use <code>HTTP POST</code> and <code>PUT</code> for articles instead of <code>PATCH</code> are as follows:</p>

                    <ul>
                      <li>Servers with <cite><a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5261" rel="cito:citesAsAuthority">XML Patch</a></cite> and mediatype <code>application/xml-patch+xml</code> (<cite><a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7351" rel="cito:citesAsAuthority">RFC 7351</a></cite>) capability in the Linked Data ecosystem are not well supported.</li>

                      <li><code>HTTP PATCH</code> with <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/sparql11-update/" rel="cito:citesAsAuthority">SPARQL Update</a></cite> (using mediatype <code>application/sparql-update</code>) would not work for RDFa representations because it would require additional server-side knowledge: HTML+RDFa serializer. This also makes server implementations a dependency for dokieli which is an undesirable design pattern.</li>

                      <li><code>HTTP PATCH</code> can help to optimise HTTP requests provided that the server processes the SPARQL query and eventually publishes the final state of the article. dokieli's use of <code>HTTP POST</code> and <code>HTTP PUT</code> on the other hand does not expect or impose operations other than to store and serve the article. If servers would like to do versioning and how, dokieli leaves it to the servers to decide.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </aside>

                  <p id="mixed-content">Due to <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/mixed-content/">Mixed Content</a></cite> implementations in Web browsers, ie. <q>fetching of content over unencrypted or unauthenticated connections in the context of an encrypted and authenticated document</q>, is subject to being blocked by the Web browser. Hence, a document available from <code>https:</code> will not be able to use the contents of a document available from <code>http:</code>. As a workaround, dokieli implements the notion of using a <a href="#preferred proxy">preferred proxy</a> that a user-agent can use in order to access the contents of an http resource. An https document fetching an https resource will not use the proxy.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="personal-identities" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#personal-identities">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Personal Identities</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p id="authentication"><strong>Authentication</strong>: Actors can authenticate themselves using <a href="#webid-tls">WebID-TLS</a> and <a href="#webid-oidc">WebID-OIDC</a> mechanisms on route to determine their level of authorization to read, write, and control resources. The workflow for authentication starts by user inputting their WebID (HTTP URI) or their Identity Provider URL as a shorthand for their WebID in dokieli UI. The Web resources in which the user wishes to interact with may be under any domain, whether self-hosted or another party's, running a server application conforming to the same standards.</p>

                  <p id="profile-description"><strong>Profile Description</strong>: In order to adopt dokieli's user-interface and the kinds of interactions that a user can perform, we dereference the user's <a href="#webid">WebID</a> (HTTP URI), and parse the <a href="#webid-profile">WebID Profile</a> document to glean the following kinds of information:</p>

                  <ul>
                    <li>Name (eg. <code>foaf:name</code> and equivalents)</li>
                    <li>Image (eg. <code>foaf:image</code> and equivalents)</li>
                    <li>Homepage (eg. <code>foaf:homepage</code> and equivalents)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#social-graph">Social graph</a> (<code>foaf:knows</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#pds">Storage</a> (<code>pim:storage</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="linked-data-notifications#inbox-notification">Inbox</a> (<code>ldp:inbox</code>, and alias <code>as:inbox</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#activitypub">Outbox</a> (<code>as:outbox</code>)</li>
                    <li>Preferences (<code>pim:preferencesFile</code>, <code>solid:publicTypeIndex</code>, <code>solid:privateTypeIndex</code>)</li>
                    <li>Preferred proxy (<code>solid:preferredProxy</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#multiple-identities">Multiple identities</a> (<code>owl:sameAs</code>)</li>
                    <li>Additional information (<code>rdfs:seeAlso</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#webid-tls-delegation">Delegated agent</a> (<code>acl:delegates</code>)</li>
                  </ul>

                  <p>When dokieli encounters <code>owl:sameAs</code> and <code>rdfs:seeAlso</code> relations in WebID Profiles, it traverses the resources continuously to mine for relevant information. The reason for this is both, to discover, as well as to fuse a graph that can be used to adopt the interface and the possible interactions. For example, driven by <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#follow-your-nose">follow-your-nose</a> type of exploration, a human-readable name, an inbox relation, list of contacts, and other information can be put together by looking at the interconnected identity graph that is semantically associated.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="creating-resources" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#creating-resources">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Creating Resources</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>An actor may require to be <a href="#authentication">authenticated</a> and <a href="#acl">authorized</a> with their <a href="#webid">WebID</a> to create Web resources.</p>

                  <p>dokieli allows write-operations for articles, annotations, and notifications. The user-interface.</p>

                  <table>
                    <caption>Registration of units and content in dokieli</caption>
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th>Purpose</th>
                        <th>Resource</th>
                        <th>Notification</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr>
                        <td>New</td>
                        <td>Actors can create new resources by inputting the location where they are authorized. New resources are an HTML+RDFa document (a basic template) with dokieli's JavaScript and CSS.</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Save</td>
                        <td></td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Save As</td>
                        <td></td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Reply</td>
                        <td>A note reply modelled around <code>oa:Annotation</code> and other data..</td>
                        <td>Sends notification using the Activity vocabulary's Announce.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Annotation</td>
                        <td>A note modelled around <code>oa:Annotation</code> and other data.</td>
                        <td>Sends notifications for <code>as:Add</code> motivated by <a href="#dokieli-bookmarking">bookmarking</a>, <code>as:Announce</code>, <code>as:Like</code> and <code>as:Dislike</code> motivated by <a href="#dokieli-assessing">assessing</a>, <code>as:Relationship</code>.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Activity</td>
                        <td>Sends activities about the annotations and encapsulates with Activity vocabulary's Create.</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Share</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                        <td>Sends notification using the Activity vocabulary's Announce about the target resource.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Citation</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                        <td><a href="#notifying-cited-entity">Notifies cited entity</a> about the citing entity's reference and the author's intention for the citation.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Archive</td>
                        <td>Sends notification using the Activity vocabulary's Announce about the target resource.</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Version</td>
                        <td>Generates a derived copy of the current document as a mutable resource including provenance.</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td>Export</td>
                        <td>Downloads the document to local system.</td>
                        <td>None</td>
                      </tr>
                    </tbody>
                    <tfoot>
                      <tr>
                        <td colspan="3">
                          <p>Any vocabulary schema:CreativeWork or one of its specialisations like <code>schema:Article</code>, <code>sioc:Post</code>, <code>prov:Entity</code>.</p>

                          <p>Notifications include information about its actor, notification date, rights and license, as well as information pertaining to the activity that it is in reference to eg. an annotation motivated by replying.</p>

                          <p>Web Annotation Data Model is used for the annotations. The annotation also includes information about its author, publication date, rights and license, system that was used to render the target resource (dokieli) for the annotation.</p>
                        </td>
                      </tr>
                    </tfoot>
                  </table>

                  <p>Documents use HTML5 <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/html-polyglot/" rel="cito:citesAsAuthority">Polyglot Markup</a></cite>. Semantics is embedded directly into human-visible prose using RDFa.</p>

                  <p>The appearance of documents is determined with CSS3. Different stylesheets can be applied to the same HTML structure so that a document can be presented flexibly, in the most appropriate way for a particular circumstance. Stylesheets can be switched from either dokieli’s menu or through Web browser with native controls, for example from a two-column layout required by an academic journal to a design in keeping with the author’s blog.</p>

                  <p>When JavaScript is enabled on the clientside, dokieli provides a rich editing interface which includes visual and structural formatting of text as well as embedding machine-readable semantics, media, dynamic citations, and inclusion of statistical charts from live endpoints. An external personal data store, or even internet connection, are not needed at this stage as modifications to a document made in the browser this way can be persisted to a local filesystem using the dokieli menu <em>export</em> function (or the browser’s <em>save as</em>), or through browser’s native local storage.</p>

                  <p>These client-triggered mechanisms and methods applied to creating resources helps fulfill the registration function.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="annotations" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#annotations">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Annotations</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>Annotations can be created to associate a node or a selection with a particular user motivation. The following motivations from the WA vocabulary can be activated by the user from dokieli's user interface: highlighting, bookmarking, tagging, commenting, describing, replying, assessing, questioning. With the exception of highlighting, all of the annotation actions can be registered and stored as a unit of information at actor's <a href="#profile-storage">storage</a>, <a href="#profile-index">registered locations</a>, <a href="#profile-outbox">outbox</a>, or article's <a href="#subject-annotation-service">annotation service</a>. The users can provide a text note for their annotations, assign a <a href="#license">license</a>, as well as designate an <a href="#subject-inbox">inbox</a> for their annotation, so that it can receive its own notifications.</p>

                  <table>
                    <caption>Implementation of Web Annotation motivations and notifications in dokieli</caption>
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th>Motivation</th>
                        <th>Method</th>
                        <th>Storage</th>
                        <th>Notification</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      <tr>
                        <th><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/annotation-vocab/#assessing">assessing</a></th>
                        <td>Assessments in the form of "approval" and "disapproval" with comments and license that can be created from and displayed in the UI. User mode: social.</td>
                        <td>Actor's preferred storage, outbox, or annotation service.</td>
                        <td>Sends notification to target's inbox about the annotation as a <code>as:Like</code> activity.</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <th><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/annotation-vocab/#bookmarking">bookmarking</a></th>
