          <section id="overview-of-web-publishing-platforms" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#overview-of-web-publishing-platforms">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Overview of Web Publishing Platforms</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>Throughout this article we have emphasised on the fundamentals of the Web architecture, Web standards and best practices with the goal of fostering interoperable information space, as well as ongoing initiatives towards the decoupling of functions in scientific communication. Hence, we reuse some of these notions to situate dokieli with the existing work on Web publishing. We focus on degree of control with respect to applications, data and identity, privacy, accessibility, and interoperability.</p>

              <p>Authoring and publishing platforms include varying characteristics of centralisation and decentralisation. It is a continuum.</p>

              <p>There is plethora of examples for centralised systems on the Web. Here we have highlight some of the platforms that are commonly known today and discuss their key architectural approaches. <span id="googledocs-medium-mediawiki"><cite><a href="https://docs.google.com/" rel="cito:discusses">Google Docs</a></cite>, <cite><a href="https://medium.com/" rel="cito:discusses">Medium</a></cite>, and <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia" rel="cito:discusses">Wikipedia</a></cite> (running <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MediaWiki" rel="cito:discusses">MediaWiki</a></cite>) are examples of Web applications for collaborative creation and publication of content.</span></p>

              <p><span id="wordpress"><cite><a href="https://wordpress.org/" rel="cito:discusses">WordPress</a></cite> is a free and open-source platform for article publication which can be self-hosted on a server controlled by the user. Visitors may sign-in with their WordPress accounts to leave comments on others’ articles, however they are typically stored by the hosting site’s database.</span><p>

              <p><span id="hypothes.is"><cite><a href="https://hypothes.is/" rel="cito:discusses">Hypothes.is</a></cite> is a server and client application that makes it possible for users to leave annotations on different types of documents on the Web using a browser extension via their proxy server. Annotations may be private or public, and can be threaded to form conversations around a piece of content. Despite allowing the attachment of annotations to resources hosted anywhere, it depends on centralised user accounts and storage space for the annotations themselves. User identity can be configured to authenticate with ORCID. A Hypothes.is client application is preconfigured to use an annotation server. Annotations can be self-hosted, however the servers do not federate.</span></p>

              <p>These systems require individual account creation and data storage with respective to their centralised services. They allow multiple participants to annotate and hold discussions around the primary content; users must access their accounts to be notified of updates to conversations, and data from both the main content and related discussion is confined to the service which was used to create it.</p>

              <p><span id="libreoffice-online">Some of the authoring and publishing systems already fulfill some aspects of decentralised systems. <cite><a href="https://github.com/libreoffice/online" rel="cito:discusses">LibreOffice Online</a></cite>'s <cite>Writer</cite>, for example, allows collaborative editing of office documents from the Web browser. Content can be stored under different CMSs in the cloud. The document’s interface consists of image tiles which are sent from the server and rendered in the browser. However, it hardly provides accessibility, rich interlinking and annotations or <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#separation-of-concerns">separations of concerns</a>.</span></p>

              <p><span id="pandoc-scholar"><cite><a rel="cito:discusses" href="https://github.com/pandoc-scholar/pandoc-scholar">Pandoc Scholar</a></cite> manuscripts to be written in plain Markdown text files, which can be converted into common publication formats, such as PDF, HTML or EPUB, using Pandoc (<a href="https://peerj.com/articles/cs-112/">Formatting Open Science: agilely creating multiple document formats for academic manuscripts with Pandoc Scholar</a>, Krewinkel, 2017).</span>

              <p><span id="smallest-federated-wiki">The <cite><a href="http://fed.wiki.org/" rel="cito:discusses">Smallest Federated Wiki</a></cite> pages to be forked and maintain personal copies.</span></p>

              <p><span id="amaya"><cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/Amaya/" rel="cito:discusses">Amaya</a></cite> is a desktop Web editor application, to create and update documents with remote access features, as well as a lightweight browser that was developed by W3C (1996-2012) to provide a framework to test its technologies. Annotations in Amaya can be attached to a Web document or a selected part of the document (without modifying the primary document) and stored locally or on a remote annotation server.</span></p>



              <p>Publicly archivable?</p>
              <p>Degree of interoperability of the protocols and formats: </p>

              <p>Level of interop.. does it create stuff that's standards compliant?</p>

              <p>can others use it? can it discover others stuff? can it reuse others stuff? is the reused and revised/enhanced reusable by other applications?</p>

              <table id="applications">
                <caption></caption>
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Application</th>
                    <th>Storage</th>
                    <th>Personal identity</th>
                    <th>Privacy</th>
                    <th>Accessibility</th>
                    <th>Interoperability</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>

                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <th><a href="https://dokie.li/">dokieli</a></th>
                    <td>Performs CRUD operations to any HTTP URI that the actor is authorised to for articles, annotations, and notifications. Offline-readable by exporting article to local disk. Uses browser's local storage for actor's profile and article cache.</td>
                    <td>Uses any WebID and allows actors to authenticate.</td>
                    <td>User and data privacy, preferred proxy, private activities</td>
                    <td>Creates content that is human and machine-readable through HTML and various RDF serialisations. Implements WCAG, ARIA, ATAG. Internationalised content and interface. Creates content that is Web archive-friendly.</td>
                    <td>Uses Linked Data vocabularies and protocols: Web Annotation, Linked Data Notifications, ActivityPub.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th><a href="https://web.hypothes.is/">Hypothes.is</a></th>
                    <td>Each application instance is configured to use a specific storage location. All CRUD operations (of that instance) performed by actors communicate with that particular location.</td>
                    <td>Each application instance is configured to use a specific identity provider eg. accounts at hypothes.is, orcid.org.</td>
                    <td>Each application instance can be configured to use different accounts of the <cite><a href="https://www.google.com/analytics/">Google Analytics</a></cite> (<abbr title="Google Analytics">GA</abbr>) tracking service. The default browser extension uses GA per active URL. Allows private annotations.</td>
                    <td>Annotations are accessible through HTML if JavaScript is enabled. JSON representation of the annotations is rendered in the DOM. Implements ARIA.</td>
                    <td>Each application instance is configured to use its own API endpoint to find annotations. A annotation serialized using the WA Data Model can be retrieved from the server's API.</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Google Drive</th>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>MediaWiki</th>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>WordPress</th>
                    <td></td>
                    <td></td>
